@phdthesis{soukup_term_1985,
  abstract = {The uses of the word, 'medium,' in communication research from 1920 through 1940 reveal a complex background of philosophical and historical development. By examining 'medium' and its development, this study argues that communication research carries with it the traces of a varied set of philosophical assumptions, many problematic and most unexamined. This varied background to contemporary work demands that the terminology of the area of study be placed in its historical, social, and disciplinary context. During the early period of communication research, 'medium' draws on four clusters of meaning: meanings associated with physical connection, meanings associated with representatives and representation, meanings associated with social formation and a social environment, and meanings associated with a secondary, instrumental, function. Educators, writers, and communication practitioners apply 'medium' to various kinds of communication, including transportation, the press, film, radio, and even language. In the 1920s these usages are specific and illustrate clear differences of meaning; by 1940 the instrumental meaning overshadows the others, as a secondary function attached to a primary denotation. The history of the word not only illumines the history of communication studies but also helps shape this area of study and its practices.},
